%S A394220 3,14,15,33,35,26,35,38,57,74,65,57,87,62,91,72,77,73,123,134,85,135,
%T A394220 95,178,123,152,159,215,187,181,203,215,309,382,247,301,213,305,219,
%U A394220 400,215,329,327,362,289,327,341,321,247,335,335,300,299,538,699
%N A394220 Largest k such that all residue classes m mod n with m coprime to n have elements a = b = m (mod n) with a,b <= k and lambda(a) != lambda(b), where lambda is Liouville's lambda function A008836.
%H A394220 Charles R Greathouse IV, <a href="/A394220/b394220.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 2..10000</a>
%H A394220 Kevin Ford and Maksym Radziwiłł, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2605.03349">Sign changes of the Liouville function in arithmetic progressions</a>, arXiv preprint (2026). arXiv:2605.03349 [math.NT]
%F A394220 Ford & Radziwiłł prove that for every e > 0, a(p) <= p^(5/2 + e) for large enough p depending on e, where p ranges over the prime numbers.
%e A394220 There are two residue classes mod 3 coprime to 3, 1 and 2. lambda(1) = lambda(4) = 1 != -1 = lambda(7) and lambda(2) = lambda(5) = lambda(8) = lambda(11) = -1 != 1 = lambda(14), so a(3) = 14.
%o A394220 (PARI) lambda(n,f=factor(n))=(-1)^vecsum(f[,2])
%o A394220 a(n)=my(mx); for(k=1,n-1, if(gcd(k,n)>1, next); my(L=lambda(k)); forstep(m=k+n,oo,n, if(lambda(m)!=L, if(m>mx,mx=m); break))); mx
%Y A394220 Cf. A008836.
%K A394220 nonn
%O A394220 2,1
%A A394220 _Charles R Greathouse IV_, May 24 2026
